-- P0-21 (SHADOW-SEMANTICS S1: shadow-hood is PER-MODULE, per-name).  A user standalone
-- that shadows an interface-method name is a shadow inside the USER's module ONLY — it
-- must never be treated as one inside the PRELUDE's own bodies.
--
-- The single-file/flat typecheck path flattened `core ++ user` into one program and then
-- applied the definer-shadow name set to every occurrence in it, core's included.  So a
-- top-level `map : Int -> Int` — even one that is NEVER USED — made the PRELUDE's own
-- `map2`/`map3`/`replaceWith`/`discard` type their internal `map` calls against the
-- USER's `map`, and `map n = n + 1` / `main = println "hello"` came back with FOURTEEN
-- errors, every one of them raised inside stdlib/core.mdk and reported at a fabricated
-- `1:0` on the user's signature (including the memorable `'map' takes 1 argument(s) but
-- is applied to 2` for a call the user never wrote).  The multi-module path was always
-- correct here: checkModuleFullImpl seeds the shadow set per module and checks core in
-- isolation.
--
-- This fixture pins BOTH halves of the rule at once:
--   * the user's `map` really is the user's inside the user's module (`map 3` → 4), and
--   * the prelude's `map` is still the METHOD everywhere inside the prelude —
--     `map2`/`discard`/`elem`/`length` are core fns whose bodies call it.
map : Int -> Int
map n = n + 1

main =
  println (map 3)
  println (map2 (a b => a + b) (Some 1) (Some 2))
  println (discard (Some 5))
  println (elem 9 [1, 2, 3])
  println (length [1, 2, 3])
